headline.main: LATER FROM MEXICO.; Santa Anna Victorious.

docs.lead_paragraph: The steamship Orizaba brings intelligence from Mexico to the 5th inst., and from Vera Cruz to the 8th. The papers which reach us announce successes of H. M. S. H. against the revolutionists. At last accounts, it will be recollected, we left him on route from Morelia, towards Zamora, where it was said they had made great preparations to give battle to him.

headline.main: GRAND K. N. DEMONSTRATION.; Samuel Seen in Broad Daylight. 20,000 AMERICANS IN THE PARK. THE PLATFORM ENDORSED. Speech of Cene, Hopkins, ex-Gov. Brown, A. J. Donnelson, Mallory, L. C. Levin, &c.

docs.lead_paragraph: There was a grand turn-out in the Park yesterday--a predigious gathering. And it was essentially an American gathering. If there were any Irish present--and there were--they did not make public their rich brogue. If there were any Germans--and there were costs of them--they kept closed months and spake especially no language but the English.

headline.main: LATER FROM HAVANA.; Arrival of the Cahawha.

docs.lead_paragraph: The U. S. Mail Steamship Cahawba, R. W. SHUFELDT, Commander, from New Orleans June 9th, and Havana 12th, arrived here yesterday morning. From Havana we have not an item of interest of a political nature to report. The Sugar market was active at high rates, but Freights falling. There were no American or foreign men-of-war in the harbor.

headline.main: THE MILITARY ACADEMY,; West Point--Close of the Examinations.

docs.lead_paragraph: On Friday, the examination of the first or graduating class of Cadets, at the United States Military Academy, West Point, was brough to a close. There was artillery and othere practice during the course of the day. One sheel, it is said, was thrown over Crow's Nest, from the battery below ROE's Hotel.

headline.main: MINNESOTA.; Extract of a Letter dated The Weather--Indians on their Way to the West.

docs.lead_paragraph: We have had almost constant June weather since April 15. On May day the prairies lay before the eye, like vast folds of softest green velvet, and English woods could not boast a richer, denser shade, or a more gorgeous tribute of flowers to that time-honored festal day.
